Rating: 4
Now one of my favorites and my guests as well. Not a real big coconut fan so changed the crust, as follows: 1 1/2 cup finely ground nilla wafers, 1 1/2 cup finely ground almonds, 1/4 cup of light brown sugar, 1/2 cup melted butter - mix together with fork until combined - butter bottom of pan and spread crust on bottom and up side of spring form pan - no need to bake, just pour in Key Lime mixture

Rating: 4
This cheesecake was excellent! Creamy and the hit of my cookout. The crust stuck to the bottom of my springform pan so the next time I make it, I would spray the bottom of the pan with cooking spray. Otherwise, the recipe worked very well. Outstanding.

Rating: 4
Great dessert but I did change a few things: 1) Crust - 1.5 cups ground nilla waffers in food processor, 1.5 cups almonds ground in food processor, 1/4 cup brown sugar, 1/4 stick butter - mix together and press on sides and bottom, no need to cook - 2) no cocoanut - just added whipped cream and sliced almonds to top - turned out GREAT!

Rating: 4
This was a fabulous cheesecake! Great flavor, more delicate than a key lime pie, and perfect cheesecake texture. This baked up exactly per the recipe, however I did bring it to room temp before refridgerating it. I used an extry teaspoon or so of key lime juice, as limes are not in season so I couldn't add zest or peel. One complaint: the crust pretty much carmelized onto the pan, and was a pain to serve and eat, plus not too attractive in chunks...I'll try another crust next time. Also: we altered the chutney quite a bit, as dried fruit sounded too weird and un-summery: we made the syrup but cooled it and added fresh diced mango and papaya, with a little pineapple juice. The syrup and fruit were drizzled over each plate and really complemented the cheesecake. Delish!

